WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:01.316
line and do that.

00:02.159 --> 00:09.568
It's also pretty interesting the neural network that they actually used was like super duper small.

00:11.202 --> 00:18.291
The input to the neural network consists of 84 by 84 by 4 image produced by this, so this is the pre-processing.

00:18.812 --> 00:29.265
The first hidden layer convolves 16 8 by 8 filters with Stride 4 with the input image and applies the rectifier non-linearity, so the ReLU.

00:29.865 --> 00:36.754
The second hidden layer convolves 32 4 by 4 filters with Stride 2, again followed by rectifier non-linearity.

00:36.734 --> 00:41.768
The final hidden layer is fully connected and consists of 256 rectifier units.

00:42.069 --> 00:47.002
The output layer is a fully connected linear layer with single output for each valid action.

00:47.784 --> 00:51.655
Number of valid actions is vary between 4 and 18 on the games we considered.

00:52.748 --> 00:56.574
Okay, as you can see, the neural network is pretty small.

00:56.635 --> 00:57.817
It's two conv layers.

00:58.438 --> 01:02.625
And as was in fashion back then, you had like big filters.

01:02.765 --> 01:05.049
So you know, big filters from like AlexNet.

01:06.631 --> 01:09.456
Yeah, big filters, but fewer than today.

01:09.616 --> 01:15.687
So today, the trend is more like deeper layers, more filters, but they are not as big.

01:15.707 --> 01:18.351
They're like three by three filters today only.

01:18.331 --> 01:21.660
Pretty interesting how they did it back then.

01:22.447 --> 01:25.050
Interesting also no max pooling and so on.

